The phases are: New Moon, Waxing Crescent, First Quarter, Waxing Gibbous, Full Moon, Waning Gibbous, Third Quarter, and Waning Crescent. The New Moon is when the Moon is completely dark and cannot be seen. The Waxing Crescent is when the Moon is partially illuminated and only a small portion is visible. The First Quarter is when the Moon is half illuminated and looks like a “D” shape. The Waxing Gibbous is when the Moon is more than half illuminated and looks like a “U” shape. The Full Moon is when the Moon is completely illuminated and exists for approximately three days. The Waning Gibbous is when the Moon is more than half illuminated but with the opposite side to the First Quarter. The Third Quarter is when the Moon is half illuminated with the opposite side to the First Quarter. Finally, the Waning Crescent is when the Moon is partially illuminated and only a small portion is visible.

inputs: Compare and contrast mitosis and meiosis.
targets: Mitosis and meiosis are two distinct forms of cell division that serve different purposes in the body. Mitosis is a type of asexual reproduction in which a single cell divides into two identical daughter cells. It is primarily used for growth, repair, and maintenance of multi-cellular organisms by providing cells for growth, wound healing, and replacing old or damaged cells. Meiosis, on the other hand, is a type of sexual reproduction that involves two rounds of cell division to produce four haploid daughter cells. It is used in the production of gametes, or sex cells, by providing genetic diversity. The primary difference between mitosis and meiosis is that mitosis produces two daughter cells with the same genetic content, whereas meiosis produces four daughter cells with half the genetic content of the parent cell.

Symptoms can be intermittent or continuous, and the disorder is often associated with depression, anxiety, and post-traumatic stress disorder.

inputs: Compare and contrast the concept of food deserts with food swamps
targets: Food deserts and food swamps are both terms that refer to the geographic availability of healthful foods. Food deserts describe areas where there is limited availability of healthful foods due to their high cost or lack of access. Food swamps refer to areas where there is easy access to less healthful, more processed and fast foods, often at a lower cost. The difference between food deserts and food swamps lies in the types of food that are accessible to people in those geographic areas. Food deserts lack access to healthy foods, while food swamps provide access to mainly processed and less nutritious foods. The causes for food deserts and food swamps vary and are largely dependent on the socioeconomic landscape of a particular region.
